Let us take the very beginning on page 1, 3 of O. P. Pr.: partibus after suis is altogether impossible, for it is evident by the following words cum aliis difficultatibus, that the author intended to point out a difficulty3 but these words form the ‘principles' of the composition.

A concrete part as such, cannot be spoken of as a diffi- cultas.

It thus becomes clearer why the gloss ‘partibus' has been smuggled in.

A scribe could only imagine a ‘composicio ἐπ’ partibus.
